I spent Christmas alone* as well, for actually the first time in my 37 years! And it was fine! I’ve been going through a really quiet and solitary sort of mood this past year or two, and it just kinda felt right in the end. I enjoyed the peace and quiet (it was a lovely day here in London so I spent a lot of time sitting in my window looking out at the park and then the sunset skies), and I did my own thing.

* I did have one family** Skype call where I opened my presents from them, and opened my own bottle of prosecco to drink “with” them (🍾🥂... all for me! 😎)

** sort of family... I mean, my ex and his family so maybe that’s weird, but hey. It was cute 🥰

And all of what you were saying about releasing all the emotions with a crying session sounds totally normal and healthy to me!

snippet.textDisplay:
Ashley, as you are one of the two YouTubers I can actually relate to, and I feel like we’re on a similar path going to find ourselves a good way through life, here are two things that helped me tremendously:
1) I started using the phrase ‚I’m working on being okay‘ instead of ‚I’m trying to be happy‘. Happy is off balance and an impossible goal to be all the time. Being okay really is a great base for your everyday life: when bad things happen, you’re normal sad which is also important, instead of being horribly depressed or bottomlessly sad, and if things go well and good things happen, you get to be happy - and not just okay because you have to make up for the subpar level of everydaylife ( and I’m not saying you’re depressed all the time! I’m exaggerating a bit to get my point across). And it’s great to be okay!
2) even though I’ve worked myself out of my depression(s) pretty much on my own (of which I’m really proud) going to my therapist is improving my life so so much. I feel like you could really benefit, too, and moving to New York would be a great opportunity for something like this long term! And you seem to be wanting to improve our way of living, I‘d say this would be perfect for you!

Anyways. Happy new year Ashley, crush 2020!
snippet.textOriginal:
Ashley, as you are one of the two YouTubers I can actually relate to, and I feel like we’re on a similar path going to find ourselves a good way through life, here are two things that helped me tremendously: 
1) I started using the phrase ‚I’m working on being okay‘ instead of ‚I’m trying to be happy‘. Happy is off balance and an impossible goal to be all the time. Being okay really is a great base for your everyday life: when bad things happen, you’re normal sad which is also important, instead of being horribly depressed or bottomlessly sad, and if things go well and good things happen, you get to be happy - and not just okay because you have to make up for the subpar level of everydaylife ( and I’m not saying you’re depressed all the time! I’m exaggerating a bit to get my point across). And it’s great to be okay!
2) even though I’ve worked myself out of my depression(s) pretty much on my own (of which I’m really proud) going to my therapist is improving my life so so much. I feel like you could really benefit, too, and moving to New York would be a great opportunity for something like this long term! And you seem to be wanting to improve our way of living, I‘d say this would be perfect for you!

Anyways. Happy new year Ashley, crush 2020!
